<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="159" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="6.[136,1452,1674,1989]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,697,1818,1844]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Distribution in Santa Maria river basin:—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[697,922,1818,1844]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Echinopsis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="6" pageNumber="159" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oxygona">
<emphasis box="[697,922,1818,1844]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Echinopsis oxygona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[937,1025,1818,1845]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[136,229,1940,1962]" captionTargetBox="[306,1282,609,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-168@7.[302,1286,605,1916]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. A) Cereus hildmaninanus (whitish-pink flowers). B) Echinopsis oxygona (pink flowers). C) Frailea albifusca. D) Frailea castanea. E) Frailea albifusca.F) Frailea lepida.G) Frailea mammifera. H) Frailea pumila. I) Frailea pygmaea.J) Frailea erythracantha K) Gymnocalycium denudatum (white flowers). L) Gymnocalycium uruguayense (yellow flowers). Pictures by A. S. Oliveira." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415611" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415611/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
), presenting a wide distribution of the study area (
<figureCitation box="[265,331,1854,1881]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="10.[136,229,1610,1632]" captionTargetBox="[306,1282,279,1582]" captionTargetId="figure-58@10.[302,1286,275,1586]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 3. A) Opuntia megapotamica (orange flowers). B) Parodia arnostiana (yellow flowers). C) P. herteri (pink flowers). D) P. linkii (yellow flower). E) P. mammulosa (yellow flower). F) P. nothorauschii. G) P. ottonis(flores yellow flower). H) P. ritteriana(yellow flower). I) P. tenuycilindrica. J) Wigginsiasellowii (yellow flower). K) W. langsdorffii (pale-yellow flower). L) W. turbinata (yellow flower). Pictures by A. S. Oliveira." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415615" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415615/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
) and in 
<collectingRegion box="[422,633,1854,1880]" country="Brazil" name="Rio Grande do Sul" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Rio Grande do Sul</collectingRegion>
, which may occur mainly in rocky outcrops, native fields associated with saxic vegetation,
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[136,1452,1674,1989]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,450,1926,1953]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Morphologic notes:—</emphasis>
This species has 8–10 ribs, with flowers. The infusiveness of rose or white-rose petals up to 
<quantity box="[165,234,1963,1989]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="159" unit="cm" value="20.0">20 cm</quantity>
long blooms from October to February, bearing fruit shortly thereafter.
</paragraph>
